# Dev-only Cloudflare OAuth prod-probe configuration.
#
# Copy this file to `.env` and put real values only in `.env`. The start task
# sources `.env` with `bash`, so quote values that contain spaces, `#`, `$`,
# quotes, or other shell-significant characters.
#
# Do not set `WT` here. The harness uses the worktree namespace from the
# repo-root `.env` loaded by mise.
#
# The probe exercises the same credential lifecycle production depends on:
# authorization code exchange, refresh-token exchange when Cloudflare returns a
# refresh token, OAuth-backed Cloudflare account discovery, account selection,
# and Cloudflare Email Sending API token-type behavior. The R2 fields below
# document the prod-like admin bucket setup this harness is expected to use as
# full provisioning and inbound probes are added.

# Local exposure for the OAuth redirect.
# Create a Cloudflare Tunnel and configure a public hostname whose service
# points to http://127.0.0.1:9003. The cloudflared container runs in the same
# Podman pod as the probe server, so 127.0.0.1 reaches the probe server.
# The token is secret. Keep it only in this ignored .env file.
# CLOUDFLARED_IMAGE=docker.io/cloudflare/cloudflared:2026.6.1
CLOUDFLARE_TUNNEL=
CLOUDFLARE_TUNNEL_HOSTNAME=cf-oauth-prod-probe.example.com

# Probe server binding inside the local Podman pod.
# PROBE_LISTEN_ADDR=127.0.0.1:9003
# PROBE_CALLBACK_PATH=/oauth/callback/cloudflare
#
# The start task owns the refresh-token store path and mounts a worktree-scoped
# local Podman volume there. Override only for targeted harness debugging.
# PROBE_REFRESH_TOKEN_STORE_PATH=/oauth-token-store/refresh-token.json

# Optional account override for offline refresh and real send validation. Leave
# empty when the OAuth grant discovers exactly one Cloudflare account.
# PROBE_CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID=

# Gated real Email Sending validation. These are not needed for the OAuth
# callback or non-sending auth probes. Use a generated test recipient, such as a
# mail-tester.net address. The confirmation string prevents accidental sends.
# PROBE_EMAIL_FROM=welcome@example.com
# PROBE_EMAIL_TO=test-generated@example.test
# PROBE_REAL_EMAIL_SEND_CONFIRM=send-real-email

# Cloudflare OAuth client.
# Dashboard path:
# - Manage Account -> OAuth clients -> Create client
#
# OAuth client form:
# - Client name: Cloudflare OAuth prod probe
# - Visibility: Public. Production needs users outside the admin Cloudflare
#   account to authorize the app, so this probe should validate the public
#   client path unless you are intentionally debugging a parent-account-only
#   private client.
# - Public client requirements: logo, Client URL, scopes, and completed Client
#   URL domain verification.
# - Response type: Code
# - Grant type / OAuth flow: Authorization Code, plus refresh token support if
#   the UI exposes it. In the API shape this is
#   `grant_types: ["authorization_code", "refresh_token"]`. The probe requests
#   `offline_access` and validates `grant_type=refresh_token`, so a client
#   without refresh-token support will not validate production behavior.
# - Token authentication method: None. The browser only follows redirects; the
#   Go probe server exchanges the authorization code from the backend boundary
#   with the PKCE verifier and no client secret.
# - Client URL / client_uri: use a stable HTTPS app/publisher URL on a domain
#   you control and can verify in DNS. Cloudflare will not promote the client
#   to public until this host is verified with the `cloudflare_oauth_client_publisher=...`
#   TXT record it provides. This is production identity metadata, not the local
#   callback. Do not use the Cloudflare Tunnel hostname here unless you can
#   complete Cloudflare's Client URL domain verification for that hostname.
# - Redirect URL: use the Cloudflare Tunnel hostname with the callback path:
#   https://cf-oauth-prod-probe.example.com/oauth/callback/cloudflare
#   This must be registered exactly as a redirect URL on the OAuth client. If
#   Cloudflare rejects a redirect URL outside the verified Client URL host, use
#   a callback path on the verified app domain and forward that path to this
#   local probe for the live validation run.
# - OAuth client type: public client using Authorization Code + PKCE.
#
# If Cloudflare redirects to `/oauth/error?error=invalid_client` or a dashboard
# "not found" page before returning to the callback, the callback server cannot
# capture that provider-side error. Run:
#   mise run //test-containers/cloudflare-oauth-prod-probe:diagnose-oauth-start
# and inspect the sanitized provider error in the current run directory.
#
# Refresh-token validation is not the initial OAuth client flow. The harness
# requests `offline_access`, exchanges the callback `code`, and then tests the
# token endpoint with `grant_type=refresh_token` if Cloudflare returns a refresh
# token. That is the production behavior this harness is validating.
#
# After creating the OAuth client, copy the generated Client ID into the
# variable below. These mirror the production admin env var names.
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_CF_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID=
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_CF_API_BASE_URL=https://api.cloudflare.com/client/v4
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_CF_OAUTH_AUTHORIZATION_URL=https://dash.cloudflare.com/oauth2/auth
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_CF_OAUTH_TOKEN_URL=https://dash.cloudflare.com/oauth2/token

# Optional setup inspection only. These are not passed to the probe server and
# are not part of the production OAuth authorization flow. Use them when the
# Cloudflare dashboard/error page is ambiguous and you need to verify that the
# configured client exists in the owning account with the expected redirect URI,
# grant types, token auth method, visibility, verification state, and scopes.
#
# Create/use a Cloudflare API token on the OAuth-client-owning account with:
# - Account -> OAuth Client Read
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_CF_OAUTH_CLIENT_ACCOUNT_ID=
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_CF_OAUTH_CLIENTS_API_TOKEN=

# OAuth scopes requested from the Cloudflare user. The canonical default scope
# list and Cloudflare permission mapping are documented in
# docs/reference/environment-variables.mdx#cloudflare-oauth.
#
# Optional debugging checkboxes, not in the default request:
# - Developer Platform -> Workers Tail: Read
# - Developer Platform -> Workers Observability: Read
# - Analytics & Logs -> Logs: Read
# Add those only when a probe actually uses them, and confirm the raw OAuth
# scope IDs from Cloudflare's `GET /oauth/scopes` before adding them here.
#
# `offline_access` is an OAuth/OIDC concept, not a Cloudflare permission
# checkbox. It is requested by default because production needs a refresh token
# to keep a connected domain grant usable after the access token expires. If
# Cloudflare rejects this scope or does not return a refresh token, that is a
# production validation result.
#
# `openid`, `email`, and `profile` are not requested by this harness by default.
# Do not select Account & Billing -> User Details unless a user-profile probe is
# added; it is not the same thing.
#
# The current send-only probe lists Cloudflare accounts with the OAuth token,
# asks you to select the account just like production setup does, then proves
# whether `email-sending.write` OAuth tokens can call
# `/accounts/{account_id}/email/sending/send` and `send_raw` for that selected
# account. The broader scope list matches the production-like domain setup flow
# we need to validate in later probes.
# AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_CF_OAUTH_SCOPES=

# Optional admin R2 archive bucket for full provisioning and inbound probes.
# Not required by the current send-only probe.
#
# This mirrors the production `AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_R2_*` shape. This is the admin
# archive bucket credential set, not the user's connected domain zone and not a
# second Cloudflare OAuth credential.
#
# From the admin perspective there are two Cloudflare credential groups:
# - the OAuth client above, used to let users connect their Cloudflare accounts
# - this R2 bucket credential set, used for the admin archive bucket
#
# Cloudflare R2 temporary credentials use the same parent R2 credential set:
# - `AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_R2_ACCESS_KEY_ID` is the R2 access key ID and is sent as
#   `parentAccessKeyId`.
# - `AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_R2_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY` is the S3-compatible secret for
#   trusted server-side archive reads/writes.
# - `AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_R2_API_TOKEN` is the parent R2 token value used only as the
#   bearer token for Cloudflare's temporary-credentials API. It is not a
#   separate broad Cloudflare API credential.
#
# The endpoint usually has the form:
#   https://<account-id>.r2.cloudflarestorage.com
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_R2_ACCOUNT_ID=
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_R2_BUCKET=agent-mail-archive
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_R2_ENDPOINT=https://example-account-id.r2.cloudflarestorage.com
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_R2_REGION=auto
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_R2_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_R2_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=
AT_EMAIL_ADMIN_R2_API_TOKEN=
